# Coding Standards

Follow SOLID principles; prefer composition over inheritance.

## Naming Conventions

-   Files/folders: `kebab-case` (e.g., `user-profile.tsx`, `cancellation-form/`)
-   Components: `PascalCase` (e.g., `UserProfile`)
-   Hooks: `useCamelCase` (e.g., `useUserProfile`)
-   Variables/functions: `camelCase`
-   Constants/enums: `SCREAMING_SNAKE_CASE` or `PascalCase`

## File Organization

-   `app/` - Pages, route handlers, page-specific components
-   `app/components/` - Page-specific components
-   `app/hooks/` - Custom React hooks
-   `app/constants/` - Constants and configuration
-   `components/ui/` - Reusable UI primitives (shadcn)
-   `context/` - React contexts
-   `models/` - TypeScript types/interfaces
-   `lib/` - Utilities and external service integrations

For components with sub-components, use a folder with `index.ts` barrel export:

```
component-name/
  index.ts           # Re-exports public API
  component-name.tsx # Main component
  sub-component.tsx  # Sub-components (flat, same folder)
  ...
  types.ts           # Component-specific types
  data.ts            # Static data/constants (optional)
```

See: `app/components/cancellation-form/`

For feature folders with multiple main components, use flat structure with co-location:

```
feature-name/
  index.ts              # Barrel exports for main components
  main-component-a.tsx  # Main components at root level
  main-component-b.tsx
  types.ts              # Shared types
  constants.ts          # Shared constants
  components/           # Flat folder for supporting components
    helper-component.tsx
    another-helper.tsx
  hooks/                # Feature-specific hooks
    use-feature-hook.ts
```

Key principles:

-   Main exported components live at the folder root (not nested in `components/`)
-   One flat `components/` folder for all supporting/shared components (no nesting)
-   One `hooks/` folder for feature-specific hooks
-   Types and constants at root level

See: `app/components/listing-page-content/sections/`

## Component Patterns

-   Use `'use client'` only when needed (client interactivity)
-   Functional components with explicit `Props` interfaces
-   Use `forwardRef` for primitive UI components
-   Add `displayName` for forwardRef components
-   **Always reuse components from `components/ui/`** (Button, Input, Dialog, etc.) unless custom requirements dictate otherwise
-   **No direct Firebase/Firestore imports or database calls in React components** - use custom hooks from `app/hooks/` instead (exception: `layout.tsx` files may access Firebase directly)

See: `context/AuthContext.tsx`, `components/ui/button.tsx`

## Custom Hooks

-   Return explicit types (define a `Result` type)
-   Use React Query for server state
-   Document complex hooks with JSDoc

See: `app/hooks/useListing.ts` (lines 25-57)

## Data Access

Use `useDataAccess` for hooks needing merchant/realtor support:

-   `effectiveTeamId`: teamId for queries (works for both account types)
-   `isRealtor`: account type flag
-   `currentTeam`: team object (null for realtors, use for role-based queries)

For permissions: `!isRealtor && hasPermission(...)` (explicit check required)

See: `app/hooks/useDataAccess.ts`, `app/hooks/useOrders.ts`

## React Query

```typescript
import { QUERY_KEYS } from '@/app/constants/query-keys';

// In hooks
const query = useQuery({
    queryKey: QUERY_KEYS.TEAM_MEMBERS.byTeam(teamId),
    queryFn: async () => { ... },
});

// Invalidating
queryClient.invalidateQueries({
    queryKey: QUERY_KEYS.TEAM_MEMBERS.byTeam(teamId),
});
```

Key principles:

-   All query keys must be defined in `app/constants/query-keys.ts`
-   Use factory functions for dynamic keys
-   Never hardcode query key arrays in hooks
-   Use `as const` for type safety and autocomplete

Common factory function names:

-   `all` - base key for bulk invalidation
-   `byTeam(teamId)` - list of items scoped to a team
-   `byId(id)` - single item by its ID
-   `byUser(userId)` - items scoped to a user

## TypeScript

-   Explicit types; no `any`
-   Prefer `const`; use `?.` and `??`
-   Extract magic values to constants
-   Functions < 50 lines
-   Only add comments where code is non-obvious

## Models/Types

-   Use enums for fixed value sets
-   Extend base types via generics
-   Colocate related types in same file
-   API model fields must use `snake_case` (e.g., `original_scheduling_id`, `start_time`). Handlers map snake_case API fields to internal camelCase params.

```typescript
export interface RescheduleSchedulingRequest extends BaseApiRequest {
    original_scheduling_id: string;
    start_time: string;
}
```

See: `models/variants/variant.ts`, `models/apis/scheduling/reschedule-scheduling.ts`

## Photo Items & Operations

**Never call `usePhotoItems` directly in components or feature hooks.** Use `usePhotoItemsContext()` from `context/PhotoItemsContext.tsx` instead. The context provides:

-   `photoItems`, `photoItemStates` - photo item data and derived state (loading, adjusted, etc.)
-   `getPhotoItemState(itemId)` - get a single item's state
-   `startOperation(itemId, op)` / `endOperation(itemId, op)` - register active operations on a photo item
-   `getActiveOperations(itemId)` - check what's in progress

For UI state derived from photo items (sidebar disabled, loader, overlays), use `usePhotoItemUIState(itemId)` from `app/hooks/photo-item/usePhotoItemUIState.ts`.

Key principles:

-   **Wrap operations with `startOperation`/`endOperation`** using `PhotoItemOperation` enum from `app/hooks/photo-item/types.ts`. Always `endOperation` in catch blocks to prevent leaked operations.
-   **For async backend operations** (e.g., object removal), don't `endOperation` on API success - use a reactive `useEffect` to end when the backend status resolves.
-   **Derive UI state from `usePhotoItemUIState`** instead of manual `isPhotoItemProcessing`/`isPhotoItemLocked` checks or custom loading `useState` + `useEffect` patterns.
-   **Never prop-drill `photoItemState`** when the component already has access to `usePhotoItemsContext()`.

See: `context/PhotoItemsContext.tsx`, `app/hooks/photo-item/usePhotoItemUIState.ts`, `app/hooks/photo-item/types.ts`

## Database Operations

Never import Firebase/Firestore directly. Use functions from `lib/firebase/database/base.ts`.

## Error Handling

-   Try/catch for async operations
-   Log errors with context before throwing
-   Use `ErrorCode` enum and `AppError` class from `app/constants/errors.ts`

## Toast / User Feedback

-   **No toast on success** — successful operations should be silent unless the action is destructive or irreversible (e.g., disabling a feature, deleting a record)
-   Always show a toast on **error** so the user knows something went wrong
